05038nam a22005655i 9780822380658DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223806587 a10.1515/97808223806582doi  a(DE-B1597)554524  a(OCoLC)1153018087  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBF713b.O93 2000 7aPSY0390002bisacsh1 aOyama, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEvolution's Eye :bA Systems View of the Biology-Culture Divide /cSusan Oyama; E. Roy Weintraub, Barbara Herrnstein Smith. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (284 p.) :b6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience and Cultural Theory00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Looking at Development and Evolution -- t1. Transmission and Construction: Levels and the Problem of Heredity -- t2. What Does the Phenocopy Copy? -- t3. Ontogeny and the Central Dogma: Do We Need the Concept of Genetic Programming in Order to Have an Evolutionary Perspective? -- t4. Stasis, Development, and Heredity: Models of Stability and Change -- t5. Ontogeny and Phylogeny: A Case of Meta-Recapitulation? -- t6. The Accidental Chordate: Contingency in Developmental Systems -- tPart II Looking at Ourselves -- t7. Essentialism, Women, and War: Protesting Too Much, Protesting Too Little -- t8. The Conceptualization of Nature: Nature as Design -- t9. Bodies and Minds: Dualism in Evolutionary Theory -- t10. How Shall I Name Thee? The Construction of Natural Selves -- t11. Evolutionary and Developmental Formation: Politics of the Boundary -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex of Subjects and Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, Susan Oyama and her colleagues in the burgeoning field of developmental systems theory have rejected the determinism inherent in the nature/nurture debate, arguing that behavior cannot be reduced to distinct biological or environmental causes. In Evolution's Eye Oyama elaborates on her pioneering work on developmental systems by spelling out that work's implications for the fields of evolutionary theory, developmental and social psychology, feminism, and epistemology. Her approach profoundly alters our understanding of the biological processes of development and evolution and the interrelationships between them.While acknowledging that, in an uncertain world, it is easy to "blame it on the genes," Oyama claims that the renewed trend toward genetic determinism colors the way we think about everything from human evolution to sexual orientation and personal responsibility. She presents instead a view that focuses on how a wide variety of developmental factors interact in the multileveled developmental systems that give rise to organisms. Shifting attention away from genes and the environment as causes for behavior, she convincingly shows the benefits that come from thinking about life processes in terms of developmental systems that produce, sustain, and change living beings over both developmental and evolutionary time.Providing a genuine alternative to genetic and environmental determinism, as well as to unsuccessful compromises with which others have tried to replace them, Evolution's Eye will fascinate students and scholars who work in the fields of evolution, psychology, human biology, and philosophy of science. Feminists and others who seek a more complex view of human nature will find her work especially congenial.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aDevelopmental psychology. 0aGenetic psychology. 0aSystem theory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / General.2bisacsh1 aSmith, Barbara Herrnstein, eeditor.4e